==English==

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|RP}} {{IPA|/əˈbæk/}}, {{X-SAMPA|/@"b{k/}}
* {{rhymes|æk}}

===Etymology 1===
* First attested circa 1200.
* From {{etyl|enm}} {{term|abak||lang=enm}}, from {{etyl|ang}} {{term|on||at, on, or toward|lang=ang}} + {{term|bæc||back|lang=ang}}; formed as ''[[a-]]'' + ''[[back]]''

====Adverb====
{{en-adv|-}}

# {{archaic}} Towards the back or [[rear]]; [[backwards]]; away.
#: ''Therewith '''aback''' she started.'' - [[w:Geoffrey Chaucer|Geoffrey Chaucer]]
# Taken by surprise; [[startled]]; [[dumbfounded]].
# {{nautical}} Backward against the [[mast]]; said of the sails when pressed by the wind from the "wrong" (forward) side.
#: ''By setting the foresail '''aback''' and the headsail in the middle one can bring a fore-and-aft rigged sailing boat practically to a halt even in heavy wind.''

=====Usage notes=====
* {{sense|taken by surprise}} Preceded by a form of the word ''take''.

